    <td style=3D'padding:.75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt'>
    <p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-bottom:12.0pt'><font size=3D1 =
color=3Dblack
    face=3DVerdana><span =
style=3D'font-size:8.5pt;font-family:Verdana;color:black'>Citing
    past scientific work in present-day research papers can be a =
slippery
    business<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> Contributions =
from
    competing labs can be glossed over<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    pertinent studies accidentally left out<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    or similar research not mentioned in an attempt to give the study at =
hand a
    sheen of novelty<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    We at <i><span style=3D'font-style:italic'>The Scientist</span></i> =
often
    hear complaints from our readers concerning what they regard as =
either
    honest or purposeful omissions in the reference lists of =
high-profile
    scientific papers<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> So =
we
    conducted a <a =
href=3D"http://www.the-scientist.com/citationamnesia/survey/">study</a>
    of our own to try and quantify the prevalence of these types of =
slights and
    ask our readers how the problem might be fixed<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    <o:p></o:p></span></font></p>
    <table class=3DMsoNormalTable border=3D0 cellpadding=3D0 =
align=3Dright>
     <tr>
      <td style=3D'padding:.75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt'>
      <p class=3DMsoNormal><font size=3D1 color=3Dblack =
face=3DVerdana><span
      style=3D'font-size:8.5pt;font-family:Verdana;color:black'><img =
border=3D0
      width=3D200 height=3D119 id=3D"_x0000_i1025"
      =
src=3D"cid:image001.jpg@01C9F65D.10675A50"><o:p></o:p></span></font></p>
      </td>
     </tr>
     <tr>
      <td style=3D'padding:.75pt .75pt .75pt .75pt'>
      <p class=3DMsoNormal align=3Dcenter =
style=3D'text-align:center'><em><i><font
      size=3D1 color=3Dblack face=3DVerdana><span =
style=3D'font-size:7.5pt;font-family:
      Verdana;color:black'>Image: Wikimedia</span></font></i></em><font =
size=3D1
      color=3Dblack face=3DVerdana><span =
style=3D'font-size:8.5pt;font-family:Verdana;
      color:black'><o:p></o:p></span></font></p>
      </td>
     </tr>
    </table>
    <p class=3DMsoNormal><font size=3D1 color=3Dblack =
face=3DVerdana><span
    =
style=3D'font-size:8.5pt;font-family:Verdana;color:black'>Indeed<st1:Pers=
onName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> the vast majority of the survey's =
roughly 550 <a
    =
href=3D"http://www.the-scientist.com/citationamnesia/results/">respondent=
s</a>
    -- 85% -- said that citation amnesia in the life sciences literature =
is an
    already-serious or potentially serious problem<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    A full 72% of respondents said their own work had been regularly or
    frequently ignored in the citations list of subsequent =
publications<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> Respondents' explanations of the =
causes range
    from maliciousness to laziness<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    &quot;It certainly shows a lot of frustration out =
there<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; Geoffrey Bilder<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    director of strategic initiatives at the UK-based non-profit =
association
    CrossRef<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> said of the =
survey results
    and the accompanying anonymous comments which respondents were =
encouraged
    to leave<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    The root of this frustration is likely twofold<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    Bilder told <i><span style=3D'font-style:italic'>The =
Scientist</span></i><st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> First<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    there is such a vast and growing body of scientific literature in =
existence
    that authors have an increasingly difficult job of finding and =
citing all
    the published work that relates to their own research<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    With modern indexing and search technologies<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    publishers and the publishing community may be able to help =
scientists
    accomplish the Herculean task of combing the =
literature<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;The joke I tell is that if you =
can help
    researchers avoid reading<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    you're going to make a lot of money<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    Bilder said<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    But there's also a certain &quot;perversion&quot; at play in the =
citation
    practices of some authors<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> Bilder
    said<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;We have =
this naive
    notion that a citation is a vote<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    Because so much of a scientific author's worth is encapsulated in =
the raw
    numerical heft of his or her citation record<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    some researchers purposefully avoid citing colleagues with whose =
work or
    viewpoints they disagree<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;The hidden motivation here is that [authors] don't want to =
give it
    any more prominence or any more of a vote than they have =
to<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; <br>
    <br>
    One of the themes to emerge in respondents' comments was simple =
resentment<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;Competitors willfully exclude =
references
    to my work and no one<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> =
even
    other colleagues<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> can =
do
    anything about it<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; one
    respondent wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> =
&quot;Papers
    published in lower impact factor journals are presumed to be second =
rate
    and ignoring/disregarding them is easy<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    wrote another<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> One =
commenter
    suggested that &quot;several papers in prominent journals including =
<i><span
    style=3D'font-style:italic'>Cell</span></i> would not have been =
accepted if
    the [past] work was cited<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    <br>
    <br>
    One early-career scientist described his harsh baptism in the =
dog-eat-dog
    world of scientific publishing<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;I
    only have 1 first author paper<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    and it was recently published (Jan 2009<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    online)<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; the =
commenter
    wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;It has =
already been
    passed over for citations by the most recent articles<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    even though it was very much on topic<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    Another commenter wrote that the main perpetrators of citation =
amnesia seem
    to be seasoned researchers<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;'big guns' who apparently feel it is safe to appropriate the =
work of
    lesser workers because the journal editors will protect =
them<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> Only junior people ever get =
nailed<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; <br>
    <br>
    Some commenters felt that American scientific authors tend not to =
recognize
    the contributions of their colleagues across the pond<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;Especially in the <st1:country-region w:st=3D"on"><st1:place =
w:st=3D"on">US</st1:place></st1:country-region>
    there is a trend to cite only papers of fellow =
citizens<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; one wrote<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;American clinical researchers tend not to read<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    or at least not to cite publications in European =
journals<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; wrote another<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    <br>
    <br>
    Other survey respondents pointed to less salacious causes of the =
problem<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> noting requests from editors to =
winnow down
    the citation lists or difficulties slogging through =
databases<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;We searched hard for papers =
that were
    relevant to our novel finding and could not find =
anything<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; one respondent =
wrote<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;We missed one that was =
apparently too
    new to be found in PubMed when we were writing our =
paper<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; Some element of the problem may =
be
    unavoidable<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> simply =
because of
    the sheer number of papers out there<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;Nobody can cite all relevant papers all the time; there are =
simply
    too many of them<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; =
one
    commenter wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> =
&quot;I do cite
    a reasonable selection of relevant papers and I don't try to pass =
off other
    peoples' ideas as my own<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; <br>
    <br>
    At least one commenter railed against the importance of citing past =
work at
    all<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;I think =
there is too
    much emphasis on history<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    the respondent wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> =
&quot;To
    cite the original paper can be a waste of time for the reader who =
wants a
    recent relevant summary rather than an 'honour' for the initial =
scientist<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; <br>
    <br>
    As for curing the problem of improper or missing =
citations<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> our survey respondents seemed evenly =
split
    between several possibilities suggested in the survey: raising =
awareness<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> random checks<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    removing editorial restrictions on citation numbers<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    signing a pledge<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> or =
including
    citations in online supplementary information<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    But several offered their own solutions<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;Referees can and should make editors and authors aware of poor
    citations<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; a =
commenter
    wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;This =
should be
    cause to refuse acceptance<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    Another commenter proposed early training<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;The practice of good citation etiquette should be taught in =
college<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> if not earlier<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    he or she wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> =
&quot;Most
    students want to cite a review article and call it a =
day<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; Still another<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    meanwhile<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> suggested =
this very
    idea to avoid inadvertent citation omissions: &quot;When there are =
many
    relevant papers<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> I've =
tried to
    find a review article that cites them<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    he or she wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    Part of the solution<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> =
though<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> may lie in changing how citations are
    formatted<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;I =
suggest to
    include a list of references as PubMed IDs<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    so all citations of a paper can be downloaded (at least as citations =
and
    URLs to pdfs) in bulk<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; one
    respondent wrote<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    Bilder agreed that revising citation formatting could go a long way =
toward
    easing frustration surrounding the issue in the scientific =
community<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;We could make it more =
informative and
    certainly more efficient<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    he said<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> Bilder said =
that by
    displaying only the minimum essential information -- author =
names<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> publication years<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    and numerical identifiers such as DOIs or PMIDs -- publishers could =
make
    room for more citations<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;That would give you enough information to recognize what =
[authors]
    were talking about if you're familiar with the =
literature<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> and if not<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    to locate [the referenced work]<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    he said<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
    <br>
    Bilder also suggested borrowing a formatting trick from citations =
that
    appear in the legal literature -- in particular<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    the parts of those citations called &quot;signals<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    which indicate why a particular work is being cited<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    Signals specify whether the citing author includes a particular =
citation as
    a comparison<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> a =
contrast<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> or an example of the point being =
made<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> Bilder said that scientific =
publications could
    adopt signals in their citations to make citing previous work more =
clear
    cut than appearing as a simple endorsement<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;Then the different kinds of citations could be treated =
differently<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; he said<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    <br>
    <br>
    But <st1:place w:st=3D"on"><st1:PlaceType =
w:st=3D"on">University</st1:PlaceType>
     of <st1:PlaceName w:st=3D"on">Chicago</st1:PlaceName></st1:place>
    sociologist <a
    =
href=3D"http://sociology.uchicago.edu/people/faculty/evans.shtml">James =
Evans</a>
    noted that some degree of citation amnesia may not be such a bad =
thing<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> as it may be indicative of a healthy =
level of
    competition for funding and recognition in the field<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;At some level<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> =
people
    fundamentally think that their work is important<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    Evans told <i><span style=3D'font-style:italic'>The =
Scientist</span></i><st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;It needs to be that =
way<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; <br>
    <br>
    Evans<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> who studies the
    relationship between markets and science<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    said that scientists design research projects anticipating that =
their
    findings will form the hub of a larger network of subsequent =
research<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> and that this expectation makes for =
good
    science<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;We want =
people to
    be gambling and to try to pick the project that they feel will be at =
the
    center of this network<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot; he
    said<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> &quot;My guess is =
that if
    you looked across scientific areas<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    he added<st1:PersonName w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> &quot;in =
really
    crowded research areas lots of people are not going to get =
cited<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> And in the most crowded =
areas<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName> people would feel the most =
neglected<st1:PersonName
    w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>&quot; <br>
    <br>
    However the life science and/or publishing communities choose to =
address
    problems with citation practice<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>
    researchers that publish their work should steel themselves for some
    disappointment down the road<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName>
    &quot;I have learned to have a thick skin<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">,</st1:PersonName>&quot;
    one survey respondent wrote<st1:PersonName =
w:st=3D"on">.</st1:PersonName> <br>
